The bash script created takes several minutes to complete, rendering it rather ineffective. By directing parts of the command to run in the background, it's possible to increase speed of completion by essentially running different parts of the command in parallel. For example:

```
#! /bin/bash

for ip in $(seq 1 255); do

ping -c1 192.168.1.$ip | grep "bytes from" | cut -d " " -f 4 | cut -d ":" -f 1 &

done
```
